<subSubSection id="C31665703273FF9883E9F9B82FDBFE4E" lastPageId="77" lastPageNumber="78" pageId="76" pageNumber="77" type="description">
<paragraph id="8BB336FB3273FF9983E9F9B82FA5F926" blockId="76.[151,1437,1663,2013]" pageId="76" pageNumber="77">
Monotypic genus represented by 
<taxonomicName id="4C0C4D783273FF998175F9B82F34F95E" authority="(Winge 1887)" baseAuthorityName="Winge" baseAuthorityYear="1887" box="[523,799,1663,1689]" class="Mammalia" family="Muridae" genus="Pseudoryzomys" kingdom="Animalia" order="Rodentia" pageId="76" pageNumber="77" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="simplex">
<emphasis id="B978EAE93273FF998175F9B82E57F95E" box="[523,636,1663,1689]" italics="true" pageId="76" pageNumber="77">P. simplex</emphasis>
(Winge 1887)
</taxonomicName>
, whose distribution ranges from north-eastern 
<collectingCountry id="F31B766B3273FF998658F9B829B3F95E" box="[1318,1432,1663,1689]" name="Argentina" pageId="76" pageNumber="77">Argentina</collectingCountry>
, western 
<collectingCountry id="F31B766B3273FF99838BF9642D76F97A" box="[245,349,1699,1725]" name="Paraguay" pageId="76" pageNumber="77">Paraguay</collectingCountry>
to eastern 
<collectingCountry id="F31B766B3273FF9982A9F9642E07F97A" box="[471,556,1699,1725]" name="Bolivia" pageId="76" pageNumber="77">Bolivia</collectingCountry>
, and from there eastward through 
<collectingCountry id="F31B766B3273FF9980D2F9642FDBF97A" box="[940,1008,1699,1725]" name="Brazil" pageId="76" pageNumber="77">Brazil</collectingCountry>
and far in the north-eastern portion of this latter country (
<bibRefCitation id="EF9D4B0A3273FF998215F9002EBFF926" author="Prado, J. R. &amp; Percequillo, A. R." box="[363,660,1735,1761]" pageId="76" pageNumber="77" pagination="1 - 120" refId="ref72147" refString="Prado, J. R. &amp; Percequillo, A. R. (2013) Geographic distribution of the genera of the tribe Oryzomyini (Rodentia: Cricetidae: Sigmodontinae) in South America: patterns of distribution and diversity. Archivos de Zoologia, 44 (1), 1 - 120. https: // doi. org / 10.11606 / issn. 2176 - 7793. v 44 i 1 p 1 - 120" type="journal article" year="2013">Prado &amp; Percequillo 2013</bibRefCitation>
; 
<bibRefCitation id="EF9D4B0A3273FF9981E1F9002FA9F926" author="Voss, R. S. &amp; Myers, P." box="[671,898,1735,1761]" pageId="76" pageNumber="77" pagination="414 - 432" refId="ref74986" refString="Voss, R. S. &amp; Myers, P. (1991) Pseudoryzomys simplex (Rodentia, Muridae) and the significance of Lund's Colletions from the Caves of Lagoa Santa, Brazil. Bulletin of the American Museum of Natural History, 206, 414 - 432." type="journal article" year="1991">Voss &amp; Myers 1991</bibRefCitation>
).
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="8BB336FB3273FF9883B9F92C2FDBFE4E" blockId="76.[151,1437,1663,2013]" lastBlockId="77.[151,1437,151,393]" lastPageId="77" lastPageNumber="78" pageId="76" pageNumber="77">
Karyotype: 2n = 56 and FN = 54. Autosomal complement: 27 acrocentric pairs large to small decreasing in size. Sex chromosomes: X, a large acrocentric; Y, a medium acrocentric (
<bibRefCitation id="EF9D4B0A3273FF9980FAF8C8284FF8EE" author="Voss, R. S. &amp; Myers, P." box="[900,1124,1807,1833]" pageId="76" pageNumber="77" pagination="414 - 432" refId="ref74986" refString="Voss, R. S. &amp; Myers, P. (1991) Pseudoryzomys simplex (Rodentia, Muridae) and the significance of Lund's Colletions from the Caves of Lagoa Santa, Brazil. Bulletin of the American Museum of Natural History, 206, 414 - 432." type="journal article" year="1991">Voss &amp; Myers 1991</bibRefCitation>
; 
<bibRefCitation id="EF9D4B0A3273FF998710F8C829B3F8EE" author="Oliveira, F. F. &amp; Langguth, A." box="[1134,1432,1807,1833]" pageId="76" pageNumber="77" pagination="19 - 86" refId="ref70469" refString="Oliveira, F. F. &amp; Langguth, A. (2004) Pequenos mamiferos (Didelphimorphia e Rodentia) de Paraiba e Pernambuco, Brasil. Revista Nordestina de Biologia, 18 (2), 19 - 86." type="journal article" year="2004">Oliveira &amp; Langguth 2004</bibRefCitation>
; 
<bibRefCitation id="EF9D4B0A3273FF9983E9F8F42DA7F88A" author="Bonvicino, C. R. &amp; Lemos, B. &amp; Weksler, M." box="[151,396,1842,1869]" pageId="76" pageNumber="77" pagination="395 - 406" refId="ref65016" refString="Bonvicino, C. R., Lemos, B. &amp; Weksler, M. (2005) Small mammals of Chapada dos Veadeiros National Park (cerrado of central Brazil): ecologic, karyologic, and taxonomic considerations. Brazilian Journal of Biology, 65 (3), 395 - 406. https: // doi. org / 10.1590 / S 1519 - 69842005000300004" type="journal article" year="2005">
Bonvicino 
<emphasis id="B978EAE93273FF99826DF8F42D6FF88A" box="[275,324,1843,1869]" italics="true" pageId="76" pageNumber="77">et al</emphasis>
. 2005
</bibRefCitation>
; 
<bibRefCitation id="EF9D4B0A3273FF9982E6F8F42E59F88A" author="Moreira, C. N. &amp; Di-Nizo, C. B. &amp; Silva, M. J. J. &amp; Yonenaga-Yassuda, Y. &amp; Ventura, K." box="[408,626,1843,1869]" pageId="76" pageNumber="77" pagination="201 - 206" refId="ref69484" refString="Moreira, C. N., Di-Nizo, C. B., Silva, M. J. J., Yonenaga-Yassuda, Y. &amp; Ventura, K. (2013) A remarkable autosomal heteromorphism in Pseudoryzomys simplex 2 n = 56; FN = 54 - 55 (Rodentia, Sigmodontinae). Genetics and molecular biology, 36 (2), 201 - 206. https: // doi. org / 10.1590 / S 1415 - 47572013000200010" type="journal article" year="2013">
Moreira 
<emphasis id="B978EAE93273FF998287F8F42E01F88A" box="[505,554,1843,1869]" italics="true" pageId="76" pageNumber="77">et al</emphasis>
. 2013
</bibRefCitation>
, pp. 203, 
<figureCitation id="13372A7E3273FF9981A1F8F42F08F88A" box="[735,803,1843,1869]" captionStart="FIGURE 2" captionStartId="7.[151,250,1191,1215]" captionTargetBox="[159,1426,281,1162]" captionTargetId="figure-69@7.[151,1436,273,1168]" captionTargetPageId="7" captionText="FIGURE 2. Distribution of diploid and fundamental number of karyotyped specimens of genus Cerradomys. (□) C. akroai; (■) C. goytaca; (ê) C. langguthi; (r) C. maracajuensis; (▲) C. marinhus; (○) C. scotti; (☆) C. subflavus; (l) C. vivoi." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.4423619" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/4423619/files/figure.png" pageId="76" pageNumber="77">Fig. 2</figureCitation>
). An autosomal heteromorphism leading to FN = 55 was reported due to the presence of a whole heterochromatic arm in one chromosome of medium-sized with one metacentric and one acrocentric element. C-banding metaphases exhibited blocks of constitutive heterochromatin on the pericentromeric region of all autosomes. On the heteromorphic pair, the metacentric element exhibited one entirely heterochromatic arm. The X chromosome presented pericentromeric heterochromatic blocks and an interstitial lightly stained C-band on its long arm. The Y chromosome presented two conspicuous interstitial heterochromatic bands on its long arm, in addition to the pericentromeric heterochromatin. G-banding was also performed. Multiple NORs, varying from five to eight were localized at the telomeric regions of the short arms of small autosomes. FISH with telomeric sequences revealed signals exclusively at the ends of all chromosome arms and no interstitial signals were observed. FISH with whole chromosome X of 
<taxonomicName id="4C0C4D783272FF988199FEE0283CFE86" authority="(HSC)" baseAuthorityName="HSC" box="[743,1047,295,321]" class="Mammalia" family="Muridae" genus="Holochilus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Rodentia" pageId="77" pageNumber="78" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="sciureus">
<emphasis id="B978EAE93272FF988199FEE02FEDFE87" box="[743,966,295,321]" italics="true" pageId="77" pageNumber="78">Holochilus sciureus</emphasis>
(HSC)
</taxonomicName>
evidenced that HSC X hybridized on the whole X chromosome of 
<taxonomicName id="4C0C4D783272FF98817FFE8C2E59FEA2" baseAuthorityName="Winge" baseAuthorityYear="1887" box="[513,626,331,357]" class="Mammalia" family="Muridae" genus="Pseudoryzomys" kingdom="Animalia" order="Rodentia" pageId="77" pageNumber="78" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="simplex">
<emphasis id="B978EAE93272FF98817FFE8C2E59FEA2" box="[513,626,331,357]" italics="true" pageId="77" pageNumber="78">P. simplex</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, but also hybridized to the pericentromeric region of the Y chromosome and produced a weak interstitial signal on its long arm (
<bibRefCitation id="EF9D4B0A3272FF98807BFEA82FCFFE4E" author="Moreira, C. N. &amp; Di-Nizo, C. B. &amp; Silva, M. J. J. &amp; Yonenaga-Yassuda, Y. &amp; Ventura, K." box="[773,996,367,393]" pageId="77" pageNumber="78" pagination="201 - 206" refId="ref69484" refString="Moreira, C. N., Di-Nizo, C. B., Silva, M. J. J., Yonenaga-Yassuda, Y. &amp; Ventura, K. (2013) A remarkable autosomal heteromorphism in Pseudoryzomys simplex 2 n = 56; FN = 54 - 55 (Rodentia, Sigmodontinae). Genetics and molecular biology, 36 (2), 201 - 206. https: // doi. org / 10.1590 / S 1415 - 47572013000200010" type="journal article" year="2013">
Moreira 
<emphasis id="B978EAE93272FF988016FEA82FB2FE4E" box="[872,921,367,393]" italics="true" pageId="77" pageNumber="78">et al</emphasis>
. 2013
</bibRefCitation>
).
</paragraph>
